Plotting function¶

In [5]:
from itertools import cycle
def plotter(history_hold, metric = 'binary_crossentropy', ylim=[0.0, 1.0]):
  cycol = cycle('bgrcmk')
  for name, item in history_hold.items():
    y_train = item.history[metric]
    y_val = item.history['val_' + metric]
    x_train = np.arange(0,len(y_val))

    c=next(cycol)

    plt.plot(x_train, y_train, c+'-', label=name+'_train')
    plt.plot(x_train, y_val, c+'--', label=name+'_val')

  plt.legend()
  plt.xlim([1, max(plt.xlim())])
  plt.ylim(ylim)
  plt.xlabel('Epoch')
  plt.ylabel(metric)
  plt.grid(True)

Analysis :The source tweet contains the main information and based on that the reply tweets can be categorised. So we can use each source tweet and a reply tweet as a pair and use a seperator like '|' between the source tweet and the reply tweet. This '|' will be encoded with a particular value by the bert model.

Analysis: From the above visualization we can conclude that the dataset is imbalanced.

  • The comment class has more records than compared to other target class
  • Comment class does not contribute much in analysing wether the tweet is a rumour or not
  • Also to deal with the imbalance in data we can first train the model to classify comment and not-comment and then classify the remaining records as SDQ(Support, Deny, Query)

The following pre-processing will be applied on the data:

  • convert all the text to lower case
  • Remove all the punctuations
  • Strip the white spaces
  • Remove the alphanumeric characters

The '|' seperator between the source tweet and the reply tweet will be retained

In [ ]:
# Preprocess the text

import re

# regular expression to remove url
url = r"(https?:\/\/(?:www\.|(?!www))[a-zA-Z0-9][a-zA-Z0-9-]+[a-zA-Z0-9]\.[^\s]{2,}|www\.[a-zA-Z0-9][a-zA-Z0-9-]+[a-zA-Z0-9]\.[^\s]{2,}|https?:\/\/(?:www\.|(?!www))[a-zA-Z0-9]+\.[^\s]{2,}|www\.[a-zA-Z0-9]+\.[^\s]{2,})"

for i in range(df_preprocess.shape[0]):
  # remove url
  preprocess_text = re.sub(url, "", df_preprocess['Text'].iloc[i])
  # remove @ and followed by the word
  preprocess_text = re.sub(r"@\w+", "", preprocess_text)
  df_preprocess['Text'].iloc[i] = preprocess_text


# convert all the text to lower case
df_preprocess["Text"] = df_preprocess["Text"].str.lower()
df_preprocess['Class'] =  df_preprocess['Class'].str.lower()

# remove all punctuations except | 
df_preprocess["Text"] = df_preprocess['Text'].str.replace(r'[^\w\s|]', '')


# strip whitespaces
df_preprocess['Text'] = df_preprocess['Text'].str.strip()
df_preprocess['Class'] = df_preprocess['Class'].str.strip()

# remove all alphanumeric characters
df_preprocess['Text']= df_preprocess['Text'].str.replace('[^a-zA-Z|\s]', '')

To deal with the class imbalance, first we will train the model on the comment Class. So the target Variable will be encoded as comment = 1, non-comment = 0

from sklearn.utils import resample
# Seperate the majority and the minority class
#df_concat = df_comment.copy()
df_majority = df_concat[df_concat.Class == 1]
df_minority = df_concat[df_concat.Class == 0]

# upsample the minority class to increase the number of samples for Class = 0 (non-comment)
df_minority_upsampled = resample(df_minority, replace=True, n_samples = 2600, random_state = 1)

# Combine the majority class(CLass = 1) with the upsampled minority class(Class = 0)
df_oversampled = pd.concat([df_majority, df_minority_upsampled])

# check the value counts to make sure the minority class is upsampled
df_oversampled.Class.value_counts()

def get_callbacks(name):
  return [
    tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min',patience=15),
    tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(logdir/name),
  ]

function to fit and compile the model

In [65]:
def compile_fit_model(train_features, train_target, val_features, val_target, model_name, name_callback, loss_function='categorical_crossentropy', perf_metric='accuracy', max_epochs=50, lr=3e-5):
  
  epochs = max_epochs
  STEPS_PER_EPOCH = 19
  #STEPS_PER_EPOCH = TRAIN_DATA_LEN//BATCH_SIZE
  num_train_steps = STEPS_PER_EPOCH * epochs
  num_warmup_steps = int(0.1*num_train_steps)

  init_lr = lr
  optimizer = optimization.create_optimizer(init_lr=init_lr,
                                          num_train_steps=num_train_steps,
                                          num_warmup_steps=num_warmup_steps,
                                          optimizer_type='adamw')

  
  METRICS = [
      tf.keras.metrics.BinaryAccuracy(name='accuracy'),
      tf.keras.metrics.Precision(name='precision'),
      tf.keras.metrics.Recall(name='recall')
  ]

  model_name.compile(optimizer=optimizer, 
                    loss= loss_function,
                    metrics=METRICS
                  )
   
  history = model_name.fit(
      train_features,train_target,
      steps_per_epoch = STEPS_PER_EPOCH,
      batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
      epochs=max_epochs,
      validation_data=(val_features, val_target),
      callbacks=get_callbacks(name_callback),
      verbose=1)
  
  return history

Build the model

In [ ]:
def build_model_comment():
  tweet_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(), dtype = tf.string, name='text')
  preprocessing_layer = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_preprocess, name='preprocessing')
  encoder_inputs = preprocessing_layer(tweet_input)
  encoder = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_encoder, trainable=False, name='BERT_encoder')
  outputs = encoder(encoder_inputs)

  model = outputs['pooled_output']
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid', name='classifier')(model)
  return tf.keras.Model(tweet_input, model)

def build_model_complex(activation_func):
  tweet_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(), dtype = tf.string, name='text')
  preprocessing_layer = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_preprocess, name='preprocessing')
  encoder_inputs = preprocessing_layer(tweet_input)
  encoder = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_encoder, trainable=False, name='BERT_encoder')
  outputs = encoder(encoder_inputs)

  model = outputs['pooled_output']
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation =activation_func)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(25, activation =activation_func)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid', name='classifier')(model)
  return tf.keras.Model(tweet_input, model)

def build_model_complex_high_acc(activation_func):
  tweet_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(), dtype = tf.string, name='text')
  preprocessing_layer = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_preprocess, name='preprocessing')
  encoder_inputs = preprocessing_layer(tweet_input)
  encoder = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_encoder, trainable=False, name='BERT_encoder')
  outputs = encoder(encoder_inputs)

  model = outputs['pooled_output']
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1000, activation =activation_func)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(500, activation =activation_func)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(50, activation =activation_func)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid', name='classifier')(model)
  return tf.keras.Model(tweet_input, model)

def build_model_complex_dropout(activation_func):
  tweet_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(), dtype = tf.string, name='text')
  preprocessing_layer = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_preprocess, name='preprocessing')
  encoder_inputs = preprocessing_layer(tweet_input)
  encoder = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_encoder, trainable=False, name='BERT_encoder')
  outputs = encoder(encoder_inputs)

  model = outputs['pooled_output']
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1000, activation =activation_func)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(500, activation =activation_func)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(50, activation =activation_func)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(model)
  model = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid', name='classifier')(model)
  return tf.keras.Model(tweet_input, model)

def build_model_simple_classifySDQ():
  tweet_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(), dtype = tf.string, name='text')
  preprocessing_layer = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_preprocess, name='preprocessing')
  encoder_inputs = preprocessing_layer(tweet_input)
  encoder = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_encoder, trainable=False, name='BERT_encoder')
  outputs = encoder(encoder_inputs)

  net = outputs['pooled_output']
  net = tf.keras.layers.Dense(3, activation='softmax', name='classifier')(net)
  return tf.keras.Model(tweet_input, net)

Build a Complex Sdq model

In [63]:
def build_model_complex_classifySDQ(activation_func):
  tweet_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(), dtype = tf.string, name='text')
  preprocessing_layer = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_preprocess, name='preprocessing')
  encoder_inputs = preprocessing_layer(tweet_input)
  encoder = hub.KerasLayer(tfhub_handle_encoder, trainable=False, name='BERT_encoder')
  outputs = encoder(encoder_inputs)

  net = outputs['pooled_output']
  #net = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1)(net)
  net = tf.keras.layers.Dense(1000, activation=activation_func)(net)
  net = tf.keras.layers.Dense(500, activation=activation_func)(net)
  net = tf.keras.layers.Dense(25, activation=activation_func)(net)
  #net = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(net)
  net = tf.keras.layers.Dense(3, activation='softmax', name='classifier')(net)
  return tf.keras.Model(tweet_input, net)

Pre-process the reddit dataset

In [74]:
def preprocess_data(df_data_preprocess):


	# Preprocess the textf

	import re

	# regular expression to remove url
	url = r"(https?:\/\/(?:www\.|(?!www))[a-zA-Z0-9][a-zA-Z0-9-]+[a-zA-Z0-9]\.[^\s]{2,}|www\.[a-zA-Z0-9][a-zA-Z0-9-]+[a-zA-Z0-9]\.[^\s]{2,}|https?:\/\/(?:www\.|(?!www))[a-zA-Z0-9]+\.[^\s]{2,}|www\.[a-zA-Z0-9]+\.[^\s]{2,})"

	for i in range(df_data_preprocess.shape[0]):
		# remove url
		preprocess_text = re.sub(url, "", df_data_preprocess['Text'].iloc[i])
		# remove @ and followed by the word
		preprocess_text = re.sub(r"@\w+", "", preprocess_text)
		df_data_preprocess['Text'].iloc[i] = preprocess_text


	# convert all the text to lower case
	df_data_preprocess["Text"] = df_data_preprocess["Text"].str.lower()
	df_data_preprocess['Class'] =  df_data_preprocess['Class'].str.lower()

	# remove all punctuations except | 
	df_data_preprocess["Text"] = df_data_preprocess['Text'].str.replace(r'[^\w\s|]', '')


	# strip whitespaces
	df_data_preprocess['Text'] = df_data_preprocess['Text'].str.strip()
	df_data_preprocess['Class'] = df_data_preprocess['Class'].str.strip()

	# remove all alphanumeric characters
	df_data_preprocess['Text']= df_data_preprocess['Text'].str.replace('[^a-zA-Z|\s]', '')

	return df_data_preprocess

Since softmax is used the output will max likelihood prob for each of the class. Find the max likelihood using the np.argmax and append it to list. So the list will contain values like (0,1,2,1,2,1). Where 0 = deny, 1 = query and support = 2.

To build a classification report and confusion matrix I am encoding the actual values of Class attribute in reddit data as "comment" : 1, "query" : 2, "support" : 3,"deny" : 4.

In [84]:
# add the prediction data from both the models to a list
final_predictions = []
for index,i in enumerate(y_predicted_li):
  
  # if the predicted value belongs to comment class value == 1 then just append it to the list
  if i == 1:
    final_predictions.append(i)

  # else the value == 0 , then find the value of non-comment class for that particular index in predict_li
  # if predict_li has value 0 which corresponds to deny then add 2 to the value and append it as 2.
  # if predict_li has value 1 which corresponds to query then add 2 to the value and append it as 3.
  # if predict_li has value 2 which corresponds to support then add 2 to the value and append it as 4.  
  else:
    category_encode = predict_li[index] + 2
    final_predictions.append(category_encode)

# conclusion: The final_preditcions list will contain the values as 1- comment, 2- deny, 3-query and 4 - support.
